reach out to cheng for 597 credit; CS 597 is a unique research course that some students pursue when working on a research project with faculty. Registration for this course works differently than other traditional courses. Registration in CS 597 requires approval from both the supervising faculty and the advising team. This independent study course which allows for students to earn course credit for individual work with CDS faculty (or officially affiliated faculty) who are approved to oversee graduate research. Policies for CS 597 differ significantly between the MCS, MS CS, and PhD programs, so it is important not to assume you can do the same thing colleagues in other programs can do. BS-MCS students can take this course under the following limits:

    Can register for 2-4 credits in a semester. Master’s students will not be approved for more than 4 credits of CS 597 in a single term.
    A limit of 4 total credit hours of CS 597 can be used toward the BS-MCS degree as additional coursework. Any excess credits after 4 will not be counted toward the degree requirements.

In order to enroll in an Independent Study interested students should first reach out directly to faculty to discuss their interest and come up with a project description. Your description should be 5-7 sentences describing the scope of work, a brief description of methods, and the expected output at the end of the semester. Next, the student should submit the project to the Siebel School Independent Study portal. The request is automatically routed to the faculty and then to departmental staff for review. If approved at both levels, you will receive an email with instructions on how to add the course to your schedule. Be sure to complete all steps in order to register for the course. Independent Study applications should indicate what your contributions will be in order to earn your grade. A CS 597 Independent Study is a graduate level course and the workload should be equivalent of what another course would have for those credit hours. Keep in mind that you are responsible for reaching an understanding with the professor overseeing your independent study on timelines, expectations, and converting outcomes to a grade. The Siebel Graduate Advising Office will not communicate with faculty on behalf of students.
